				\begin{document}$$\{T(r,t),\,P(r,t)\}=\sum _{n}\{{B}_{n}(r,t),\,{Z}_{n}(r,t)\}{T}_{n}(t).$$\end{document}{T(r,t),P(r,t)}=∑n{Bn(r,t),Zn(r,t)}Tn(t).

Namely, the loading vectors of the two variables, Bn(r, t) and Zn(r, t), share an identical PC time series, Tn(t), for each mode n. As a result, the evolution of a physical process manifested as Bn(r, t) and Zn(r, t) in two different variables is governed by a single amplitude time series. Otherwise, Bn(r, t) and Zn(r, t) do not represent the same physical process and henceforth are not physically consistent. This process can be repeated for as many predictor variables as needed. As a result of regression, then, entire data can be written in the form12\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Data(r,t)=\sum _{n}\{{B}_{n}(r,t),{Z}_{n}(r,t),{U}_{n}(r,t),\ldots \}{T}_{n}(t),$$\end{document}Data(r,t)=∑n{Bn(r,t),Zn(r,t),Un(r,t),…}Tn(t),where the terms in curly braces denote physically consistent evolutions derived from various physical variables. A rigorous mathematical explanation of the regression analysis in CSEOF space can be found in Kim48.
